        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s4" slide="4" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="2" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="2" slide="4">order</keyword><keyword chapter="2" slide="4">order</keyword><keyword chapter="2" slide="4">infinite order</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="01838c350283198a9a47e82d7a337b70" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="4" item="2.1">
Let $G$ be a group, with identity element $e$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">order</xh:b> of $G$ is the number of elements in $G$.
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment="statement"/>
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">order</xh:b> $\ord g$ of an <xh:i xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"> element</xh:i> $g \in G$
is the smallest $n \in \mathbb{N}$ such that $g^n = e$.
If no such $n$ exists, we say that $g$ has <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">infinite order</xh:b>.
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="2" label="thm:orderdividesn" md5="682fc761ecf19d9c07d8b7b1a587af06" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="4" item="2.2">

<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Let $G$ be a group with identity element $e$.
Let $g$ be an element of $G$.  If $g^n = e$ for some $n \in \mathbb{N}$,
then $\ord g$ is finite, and moreover $\ord g$ divides $n$.
</newcol></statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="723807213862930cca60acb6037d74ca" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="4" of="682fc761ecf19d9c07d8b7b1a587af06">
Shown in class.
</substatement>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment=""/>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="3" md5="7f335260865edba17debc220ef37b93d" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="4" item="2.3">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
If $G$ has finite order, then every element of $G$ has finite order.
</newcol>
</statement>
<xh:br xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" wbtag="newline" environment=""/>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="2" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="2" slide="5">cyclic</keyword><keyword chapter="2" slide="5">generator</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="4" md5="81ee385eb9d7fc5f03e06028f10fac58" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="5" item="2.4">
A group $G$ is <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">cyclic</xh:b> if there exists $g \in G$ such that every element of $G$ is equal to $g^n$
for some integer $n$.
In which case, we write: $G = \langle g \rangle$, and say that $g$ is a <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">generator</xh:b> of $G$.
<xh:p xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/>
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Note: The generator of of a cyclic group might not be unique.
</newcol>
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="5" md5="017f6531a1e2c99e5d46a67e99a9dc05" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="5" item="2.5">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
<!--
$(\mathbb{Z}_m, +)$ is cyclic, generated by $1$, or any integer $n \in \mathbb{Z}_m$
such that $gcd(m, n) = 1$.
-->
$(U_m, \cdot)$ is cyclic.
</newcol>
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="6" md5="12b03f3119341f000182eeea2f370ca3" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="5" item="2.6">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
A finite cyclic group $G$ has order (i.e. size) $n$
if and only if each of its generators has order $n$.
</newcol>
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="7" md5="310302137df5a62dc62619ddae49df2c" course="Math 2070" chapter="2" slide="5" item="2.7">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
$(\mathbb{Q}, +)$ is not cyclic.
</newcol>
</statement>
